    category: "CULTURAL_VILLAGE",
    summary: `Butwal is a major commercial and transit city in Rupandehi at around 200 m elevation, positioned at the critical junction of the Mahendra and Siddhartha highways. It serves as the main gateway to Lumbini, Tansen and the hills of western Nepal, and is a busy, growing hub with a rich river-front character.`,
    story: `<p>Butwal occupies one of the most strategically important positions in Nepal's road network: the junction where the Mahendra Highway (running east–west across the Terai) meets the Siddhartha Highway (climbing north into the hills toward Tansen, Pokhara, and ultimately Mustang). This location has made Butwal one of the most important commercial and transit cities in western Nepal, a place through which an extraordinary volume of goods, vehicles, and people move each day.</p><p>The city sits at approximately 200 metres above sea level on the banks of the Tinau River, which rushes out of the Siwalik Hills just north of town before spreading across the flat Terai plains. The Tinau Riverfront has become a focal point for leisure and recreation, with a promenade, parks, and restaurants giving Butwal a pleasant public face that belies its reputation as primarily a transit stop. The city's main bazaars are dense, energetic, and full of the commercial vitality of a place that has been an important crossroads for centuries.</p><p>Butwal serves as the practical gateway to the UNESCO World Heritage Site of Lumbini (approximately 22 km west), and most travellers heading to the birthplace of the Buddha pass through or stop in the city. It is also the most convenient base for visiting Tansen (80 km north by the Siddhartha Highway), the historic Newari hill town famous for its metalwork and Rani Mahal. For travellers coming from India via the Sunauli border crossing, Butwal is often the first substantial Nepali city encountered.</p><p>The city is growing rapidly, with new hospitals, colleges, industrial estates, and hotel developments transforming it from a mere transit hub into a substantial urban centre. The Tinau corridor north of Butwal into the Siwalik hills offers pleasant cycling and motorbike day trips, and the surrounding Terai is notable for bird watching along the river edges where kingfishers, herons, and seasonal waterfowl congregate in large numbers.</p>`,
