    name: `Diktel`,
    category: "CULTURAL_VILLAGE",
    summary: `Diktel is the hill headquarters of Khotang district in eastern Nepal at 1,631 m, a quiet bazaar town serving as the base for visiting the sacred Halesi-Maratika cave complex — one of the holiest Buddhist and Hindu pilgrimage sites in the Himalaya — and the forest trails of the remote Khotang hills.`,
    story: `<p>Diktel sits on a ridge in the Khotang hills of eastern Nepal at 1,631 metres, a compact district headquarters that sees relatively few foreign visitors yet occupies an important position as the administrative and commercial centre of one of Nepal's more remote mid-hill districts. The town itself is modest — a main bazaar street of shops and tea stalls, a district hospital, and a scattering of government offices — but its strategic importance lies in its proximity to the Halesi-Maratika cave complex, one of the most sacred pilgrimage destinations in all of Buddhism.</p><p>The Halesi-Maratika caves, located roughly 15 kilometres from Diktel near the town of Halesi, are revered as the site where the great Tibetan Buddhist master Padmasambhava (Guru Rinpoche) attained longevity siddhi through meditation, accompanied by the Indian tantric master Humkara and the princess Mandarava. Both Hindus and Buddhists regard the caves as supremely sacred: Hindus identify the main cave as an abode of Lord Shiva (Mahadev) and a Jyotirlinga site, while Buddhists venerate the caves as one of the most powerful practice places of Guru Rinpoche in all of South Asia. Pilgrims from across Nepal, India, Tibet, and the global Tibetan Buddhist community converge here especially during the Tibetan New Year celebrations in February and March.</p><p>The surrounding Khotang hills offer excellent trekking through traditional Rai and Magar communities, dense rhododendron forests that blaze with colour from February to April, and dramatic ridge-top viewpoints commanding panoramas of the eastern Himalaya. Lamidanda Airport, located 25 kilometres north of Diktel, provides the main air access to the district from Kathmandu, making Diktel a manageable destination for those willing to combine a short flight with local transport.</p><p>Khotang is also notable as one of the original homeland districts of the Kirat-Rai people, whose shamanic religious practice (Mundhum) and distinctive oral literature represent one of Nepal's oldest surviving indigenous traditions. A visit to Diktel and its surrounding villages offers a rare encounter with a culture that has maintained its identity with remarkable tenacity through centuries of political change.</p>`,
