    summary: `Dhankuta is a remarkably clean and picturesque Newari hill town at 1,150 m in eastern Nepal, often proposed as Nepal's cleanest city, perched on a ridge above the Arun and Tamor river valleys with sweeping views of Everest, Makalu, Kangchenjunga, and sixteen districts from the Dhoje Danda viewpoint.`,
    story: `<p>Dhankuta stands on a long ridge in the hills of eastern Nepal at 1,150 metres, a town whose character is shaped as much by its Newari heritage and civic pride as by its extraordinary geographical setting. Proposed as Nepal's cleanest city by The Kathmandu Post, Dhankuta maintains an orderliness and quiet dignity unusual in Nepali hill towns: whitewashed stone houses with carved wooden facades line the main bazaar, bougainvillea spills over compound walls, and the streets are swept clean each morning by residents who take visible pride in the appearance of their community.</p><p>Until around 1963, Dhankuta served as the administrative headquarters for the entire north-eastern region of Nepal, and the old Bada Hakim's compound above the town still hints at this former authority. The bazaar retains a traditional Newari character, with metalworkers, weavers, and spice traders occupying shops that have been in the same families for generations. The weekly market draws villagers from the surrounding hills who descend to trade in a tradition unchanged over centuries.</p><p>The greatest reward of Dhankuta is the view. From the Dhoje Danda ridge above the town — reached by a pleasant two-hour walk through pine forest — the panorama encompasses sixteen districts of Nepal's hills and Terai plains, and on the northern horizon the Himalayan giants emerge with stunning clarity: Sagarmatha (Everest) at 8,848 m, Makalu at 8,463 m, Lhotse at 8,516 m, Kangchenjunga at 8,586 m, and Kumbhakarna (Jannu) at 7,710 m. In the evening, the same ridge offers one of Nepal's finest sunset views as the peaks turn from gold to orange to deep crimson against a violet sky.</p><p>Dhankuta lies on the route between the lowland city of Dharan and the hill trading post of Hile, from which trekkers historically set out for the Arun Valley and Makalu Base Camp. The town makes an excellent overnight stop on this journey, offering comfortable lodges, good food, and the quiet pleasure of walking streets that feel genuinely cared for in a country where civic maintenance is often a secondary priority.</p>`,
